00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:39.850
and the s in the z direction
can be plus 1/2 or minus 1/2.

00:27:39.850 --> 00:27:43.330
s is 3/2 and then s in
the z direction can be m

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:47.820
is 3/2, 1/2, minus
1/2, minus 3/2.

00:27:47.820 --> 00:27:49.110
OK.

00:27:49.110 --> 00:27:52.010
Other questions?

00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:53.798
OK, yeah.

00:27:53.798 --> 00:27:56.280
AUDIENCE: What about the
lowering and raising of those?

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:58.652
PROFESSOR: Good, we're going
to have to construct them,

00:27:58.652 --> 00:27:59.610
because, what are they?

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.110
Well, they lower
and raise, so we're

00:28:01.110 --> 00:28:03.591
going to have to build the
states that lower and raise.

00:28:03.591 --> 00:28:06.007
AUDIENCE: And would lowering
on the up will give you down,

00:28:06.007 --> 00:28:08.579
but raising on up--?

00:28:08.579 --> 00:28:09.370
PROFESSOR: Awesome.

00:28:09.370 --> 00:28:11.709
So what did it mean
that we had towers?

00:28:11.709 --> 00:28:12.750
Let me do that back here.

00:28:12.750 --> 00:28:14.329
So the question is,
look, we're going

00:28:14.329 --> 00:28:16.370
to have to use the raising
and lowering operators

00:28:16.370 --> 00:28:17.995
at the end of the
day, but what happens

00:28:17.995 --> 00:28:20.790
if I raise the bottom
state-- what if I raise down?

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:23.010
I'll get up.

00:28:23.010 --> 00:28:25.940
And what happens if I raise up?

00:28:25.940 --> 00:28:26.670
You get 0.

00:28:26.670 --> 00:28:30.270
That's the statement
that the tower ends.

00:28:30.270 --> 00:28:33.810
On the other hand, if s is 3/2,
what happens if I raise 1/2?

00:28:33.810 --> 00:28:34.800
I get 3/2.

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:38.070
And if I raise 3/2, I get
nothing, I get 0, identically.

00:28:38.070 --> 00:28:39.950
And that's the statement
that the tower ends.

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:42.360
So for every tower
labeled by s, we

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:47.390
have a set of states labeled by
m which goes from minus s to s

00:28:47.390 --> 00:28:48.750
in integer steps.

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:50.430
The raising operator
raises us by 1,

00:28:50.430 --> 00:28:52.100
the lowering
operator lowers by 1.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:54.300
The lowering operator
annihilates the bottom state,

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:57.140
the raising operator
kills the top state.

00:28:57.140 --> 00:28:58.510
Cool?

00:28:58.510 --> 00:28:59.254
Yeah.

00:28:59.254 --> 00:29:01.110
AUDIENCE: Do states
like 3/2 and 5/2

00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:03.430
have anything akin
to up and down?

00:29:03.430 --> 00:29:05.110
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
so-- do they have

00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:06.460
anything akin to up and down.

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:08.097
Up and down is just a name.

00:29:08.097 --> 00:29:09.930
It doesn't really
communicate anything other

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:14.750
than it's shorthand for
spin in the z direction 1/2.

00:29:14.750 --> 00:29:17.300
So the question could
be translated as,

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.350
are there convenient
and illuminating names

00:29:19.350 --> 00:29:21.190
for the spin 3/2 states?

00:29:21.190 --> 00:29:24.010
And I don't really know.

00:29:24.010 --> 00:29:26.059
I don't know.

00:29:26.059 --> 00:29:27.100
I mean, the states exist.

00:29:27.100 --> 00:29:28.400
So we can build
nuclear particles that

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:30.691
have angular momentum 3/2,
or 5/2, all sorts of things.

00:29:30.691 --> 00:29:32.940
But I don't know
of a useful name.

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:34.728
For the most part,
we simplify our life

00:29:34.728 --> 00:29:35.936
by focusing on the 1/2 state.

00:29:35.936 --> 00:29:39.740
And as you'll discover in
8.05, the spin 1/2 states,

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:41.320
if you know them
very, very well,

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:43.611
you can use everything you
know about them to construct

00:29:43.611 --> 00:29:47.700
all of the spin 5/2 8/2--
well, 8/2 is stupid, but-- 9/2,

00:29:47.700 --> 00:29:49.410
all those from the spin 1/2.

00:29:49.410 --> 00:29:52.290
So it turns out spin
1/2 is sort of Ur--

00:29:52.290 --> 00:29:53.940
in a way that can be
made very precise,

00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:55.010
and that's the theory
of Lie algebras.

00:29:55.010 --> 00:29:55.509
Yeah.

00:29:58.089 --> 00:29:59.755
AUDIENCE: Can you
just elaborate on what

00:29:59.755 --> 00:30:02.171
you meant by, you can't really
think of spin as an angular

00:30:02.171 --> 00:30:03.200
momentum vector?

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:04.340
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:30:04.340 --> 00:30:05.030
So OK, good.

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:07.654
So the question is, elaborate a
little bit on what you mean by,

00:30:07.654 --> 00:30:10.160
spin can't be thought of as
an angular momentum vector.

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:13.590
Spin certainly can be thought
of as an angular momentum,

00:30:13.590 --> 00:30:17.620
because the whole point here
was that if you have a charged

00:30:17.620 --> 00:30:23.980
particle and it carries spin,
then it has a magnetic moment.

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:25.840
And a magnetic
moment is the charge

00:30:25.840 --> 00:30:28.950
times the angular momentum.

00:30:28.950 --> 00:30:31.250
So if it carries spin,
and it carries charge,

00:30:31.250 --> 00:30:33.334
and thus it carries
magnetic moment--

00:30:33.334 --> 00:30:35.500
that's pretty much what we
mean by angular momentum.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:38.470
That's as good a
diagnostic as any.

00:30:38.470 --> 00:30:42.230
Meanwhile, on top of satisfying
that experimental property,

00:30:42.230 --> 00:30:44.300
this, just as a set of
commutation relations,

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:46.674
these commutation relations
are the commutation relations

00:30:46.674 --> 00:30:47.581
of angular momentum.

00:30:47.581 --> 00:30:50.080
It just turns out that we can
have states with total angular

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:54.360
momentum little s, which is 1/2
integral-- 1/2, 3/2, et cetera.

00:30:54.360 --> 00:30:56.940
Now, the things that I want
to emphasize are twofold.

00:30:56.940 --> 00:30:58.390
First off, something I've
harped on over and over again,

00:30:58.390 --> 00:31:00.690
so I'll attempt to limit
my uses of this phrase.

00:31:00.690 --> 00:31:05.530
But you cannot think of these
states with s is 1/2 as wave

00:31:05.530 --> 00:31:07.564
functions determining
position on a sphere.

00:31:07.564 --> 00:31:08.980
So that's the first
sense in which

00:31:08.980 --> 00:31:11.350
you can't think of it as
equivalent to orbital angular

00:31:11.350 --> 00:31:11.850
momentum.

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:12.800
But there's a
second sense, which

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:15.169
is that up and down should
not be thought of as spin

00:31:15.169 --> 00:31:17.710
in the z direction being up and
spin in the z direction being

00:31:17.710 --> 00:31:20.152
down meaning a vector in
three dimensions pointing up

00:31:20.152 --> 00:31:22.110
and a vector in three
dimensions pointing down,

00:31:22.110 --> 00:31:23.550
because those states
are orthogonal.

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:25.341
Whereas these two
three-dimensional vectors

00:31:25.341 --> 00:31:27.230
are not orthogonal--
they're parallel.

00:31:27.230 --> 00:31:29.310
They have a non-zero
inner product.

00:31:29.310 --> 00:31:34.730
So up and down, the names we
give these spin 1/2 states,

00:31:34.730 --> 00:31:37.310
should not be confused with
pointing up in the z direction

00:31:37.310 --> 00:31:39.070
and down in the z direction.

00:31:39.070 --> 00:31:43.710
It's just a formal name we give
to the plus 1/2 and minus 1/2

00:31:43.710 --> 00:31:46.070
angular momentum in
z direction states.

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:47.575
Does that answer your question?

00:31:47.575 --> 00:31:48.952
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
so, when you make

00:31:48.952 --> 00:31:50.452
a measurement of
the value of spin--

00:31:50.452 --> 00:31:52.517
so perhaps you do a
Stern-Gerlach experiment--

00:31:52.517 --> 00:31:55.580
and you get what
the spin is, can you

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:59.895
not then say, all right, this
is spin plus 1/2, spin minus?

00:31:59.895 --> 00:32:04.244
It's as z is positive
1/2 as z is minus 1/2?

00:32:04.244 --> 00:32:05.410
PROFESSOR: Yeah, absolutely.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:07.076
So if you do a
Stern-Gerlach experiment,

00:32:07.076 --> 00:32:09.594
you can identify those
electrons that had spin plus 1/2

00:32:09.594 --> 00:32:11.010
and those that had
spin minus 1/2,

00:32:11.010 --> 00:32:12.650
and they come out
in different places.

00:32:12.650 --> 00:32:13.920
That's absolutely true.

00:32:13.920 --> 00:32:16.369
I just want to emphasize
that the up vector does not

00:32:16.369 --> 00:32:17.785
mean that they're
somehow attached

00:32:17.785 --> 00:32:21.840
to the electronic vector that's
pointing in the z direction.

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:22.340
Good.

00:32:22.340 --> 00:32:22.840
Yeah.

00:32:25.050 --> 00:32:26.000
Go ahead, whichever.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.580
AUDIENCE: How do we verify that
uncharged particles have spin?

00:32:29.580 --> 00:32:31.580
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's
an interesting question.

00:32:31.580 --> 00:32:33.690
So the question
is, how do we know

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:35.720
if an uncharged
particle has spin?

00:32:35.720 --> 00:32:37.150
And there are many
ways to answer

00:32:37.150 --> 00:32:39.877
this question,
one of which we're

00:32:39.877 --> 00:32:41.960
going to come to later
which has to do with Bell's

00:32:41.960 --> 00:32:44.180
inequality, which is a
sort of slick way to do it.

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:46.640
But a very coarse
way is this way.

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:48.772
We believe, in a deep
and fundamental way,

00:32:48.772 --> 00:32:50.730
that the total angular
momentum of the universe

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:52.990
is conserved, in
the following sense.

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:56.757
There's no preferred
axis in the universe.

00:32:56.757 --> 00:32:58.340
If you're a cosmologist,
just stay out

00:32:58.340 --> 00:32:59.881
of the room for the
next few minutes.

00:32:59.881 --> 00:33:02.260
So there's no preferred
axis in the universe

00:33:02.260 --> 00:33:05.259
and the law of physics should
be invariant under rotation.

00:33:05.259 --> 00:33:07.550
Now, if you take a system
that has a bunch of particles

00:33:07.550 --> 00:33:10.960
with known angular momentum--
let me give you an example.

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:12.215
Take a neutron.

00:33:12.215 --> 00:33:14.990
A neutron has spin 1/2.

00:33:14.990 --> 00:33:17.090
Wait, how did I know that?

00:33:17.090 --> 00:33:20.960
We can do that experiment by
doing the following thing.

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:23.610
We can take a neutron
and bind it to a proton

00:33:23.610 --> 00:33:27.170
and see that the resulting
object has spin 1.

00:33:27.170 --> 00:33:30.910
So let me try to think of a way
that doesn't involve a neutron.

00:33:30.910 --> 00:33:38.020
Grant me for the moment that
you know that a neutron has

00:33:38.020 --> 00:33:39.610
spin 1/2.

00:33:39.610 --> 00:33:43.340
So let's just imagine that we
knew that, by hook or by crook.

00:33:43.340 --> 00:33:46.270
We then do the
following experiment.

00:33:46.270 --> 00:33:47.420
We wait.

00:33:47.420 --> 00:33:49.180
Take a neutron, let
it sit in empty space.

00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:51.430
When that neutron decays,
it does a very cool thing.

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:54.340
It decays relatively
quickly into your proton

00:33:54.340 --> 00:33:56.218
and an electron that you see.

00:33:56.218 --> 00:33:58.676
You see them go flying away
the proton has positive charge,

00:33:58.676 --> 00:34:01.359
and the electron has negative
charge and it goes flying away.

00:34:01.359 --> 00:34:02.400
But you've got a problem.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:06.285
Because you knew that
the neutron had spin 1/2,

00:34:06.285 --> 00:34:07.160
which is [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:07.160 --> 00:34:09.219
And then you decay one into
a proton and an electron.

00:34:09.219 --> 00:34:10.719
And the total angular
momentum there

00:34:10.719 --> 00:34:13.150
is 1/2 plus 1/2
or 1/2 minus 1/2.

00:34:13.150 --> 00:34:14.850
It's either 1 or 0.

00:34:14.850 --> 00:34:16.726
And you've got a problem.

00:34:16.726 --> 00:34:18.350
Angular momentum
hasn't been conserved.

00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:20.929
So what do you
immediately deduce?

00:34:20.929 --> 00:34:23.560
That another particle must
have also been emitted

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:25.690
that had 1/2 integer
angular momentum

00:34:25.690 --> 00:34:27.150
to conserve angular momentum.

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:30.107
And it couldn't carry any
charge because the electron

00:34:30.107 --> 00:34:32.440
and the proton were neutral,
and the neutron is neutral.

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:34.497
So things like
this you can always

00:34:34.497 --> 00:34:36.330
deduce from conservation
of angular momentum

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:37.204
one way or the other.

00:34:37.204 --> 00:34:39.219
But the best way
to do it is going

00:34:39.219 --> 00:34:42.151
to be some version of
addition of angular momentum

00:34:42.151 --> 00:34:44.484
where you have some object
like an electron and a proton

00:34:44.484 --> 00:34:46.670
and you allow them
to stick together

00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:48.380
and you discover it
has total spin 1.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:52.260
Yeah.

00:34:52.260 --> 00:34:53.889
We can talk about that in
more detail afterwards.

00:34:53.889 --> 00:34:55.449
That's a particularly nice
way to do the experiment.

00:34:55.449 --> 00:34:55.949
Yeah.

00:34:58.374 --> 00:35:00.779
AUDIENCE: Angular momentum
[INAUDIBLE] weird vector

00:35:00.779 --> 00:35:07.032
since if you reflect your
system through [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:07.032 --> 00:35:07.977
How does that work?

00:35:07.977 --> 00:35:09.060
PROFESSOR: Yeah, OK, good.

00:35:09.060 --> 00:35:10.500
I don't want to get into
this in too much detail,

00:35:10.500 --> 00:35:12.958
but it's a really good question,
so come to my office hours

00:35:12.958 --> 00:35:14.850
and ask or go to
recitations and ask.

00:35:14.850 --> 00:35:16.016
It's a really good question.

00:35:16.016 --> 00:35:18.360
The question is this--
angular momentum

00:35:18.360 --> 00:35:21.790
has a funny property under
parity, under reflection.

00:35:21.790 --> 00:35:25.720
So if you look in a mirror this
way, here's angular momentum

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:27.390
and it's got--
right-hand rule, it's

00:35:27.390 --> 00:35:29.473
got angular momentum up--
if I look in the mirror,

00:35:29.473 --> 00:35:31.270
it's going this way.

00:35:31.270 --> 00:35:35.520
So it would appear to have
right angular momentum down.

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:38.110
That's what it looks like
if you reflect in a mirror.

00:35:38.110 --> 00:35:39.060
Other direction.

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:41.974
So that's a funny property
of angular momentum.

00:35:41.974 --> 00:35:43.890
It's also a true property
of angular momentum.

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:45.460
It's fine.

00:35:45.460 --> 00:35:47.832
And what about spin,
is the question.

00:35:47.832 --> 00:35:50.040
Does spin also have this
funny property under parity,

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:52.160
is that basically the question?

00:35:52.160 --> 00:35:53.380
Yeah, and it does.

00:35:53.380 --> 00:35:55.710
And working out exactly
how to show that

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:57.210
is a sort of
entertaining exercise.

00:35:57.210 --> 00:35:59.470
So again, it's beyond
the scope of the lecture,

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:02.630
so come ask me in office hours
and we can talk about that.

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:03.420
Yeah, one more.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:06.348
AUDIENCE: For orbital angular
momentum, say for l equals 1,

00:36:06.348 --> 00:36:09.139
we had states like m
equals plus 1 and minus 1.

00:36:09.139 --> 00:36:09.764
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:36:09.764 --> 00:36:14.400
AUDIENCE: And we did think
of those as angular momentum

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:15.140
vectors.

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:15.495
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:36:15.495 --> 00:36:17.778
AUDIENCE: But those states are
also orthogonal, are they not?

00:36:17.778 --> 00:36:19.195
PROFESSOR: Yeah, those
states are also orthogonal.

00:36:19.195 --> 00:36:21.794
AUDIENCE: So even though
the angular momentum vectors

00:36:21.794 --> 00:36:23.210
aren't orthogonal,
they're still--

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:24.497
it's just a different sense.

00:36:24.497 --> 00:36:25.830
PROFESSOR: That's exactly right.

00:36:25.830 --> 00:36:28.497
So again, even in the case
of integer angular momentum,

00:36:28.497 --> 00:36:30.080
you've got to be
careful about talking

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:32.440
about the top state
and the bottom state

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:34.960
corresponding to pointing
in some direction,

00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:36.680
because they're
orthogonal states.

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:39.180
However, they do correspond to
a particular angular momentum

00:36:39.180 --> 00:36:40.770
vector in three
dimensional space.

00:36:40.770 --> 00:36:42.980
They correspond to a
distribution on the sphere.

00:36:42.980 --> 00:36:45.070
So there's a sense in
which they do correspond

00:36:45.070 --> 00:36:47.356
to real rotations, real
eigenfunctions on a sphere,

00:36:47.356 --> 00:36:49.230
and there's also a sense
in which they don't,

00:36:49.230 --> 00:36:50.605
because they're
still orthogonal.

00:36:50.605 --> 00:36:51.810
That's exactly right.

00:36:51.810 --> 00:36:52.580
So let me move on.

00:36:52.580 --> 00:36:55.190
I'm going to stop
questions at this point.

00:36:55.190 --> 00:37:00.150
So good.

00:37:00.150 --> 00:37:01.770
So these are the
properties that need

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:04.140
to be satisfied
by our operators.

00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:08.360
And it's pretty easy to
see in this basis what

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:09.850
these operators must be.

00:37:09.850 --> 00:37:12.660
Sz has eigenvectors
1, 0 and 0, 1.

00:37:12.660 --> 00:37:18.640
So Sz should be equal to h
bar upon 2 1, 0, 0, minus 1.

00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:22.480
So let's just check
this on 1, 0 gives me 1,

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:26.550
0, so it gives me the same
thing back times h bar upon 2.

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:27.050
Cool.

00:37:27.050 --> 00:37:29.460
And acting on 0, 1,
or the down state,

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:32.270
we get h bar upon
2 times 0 minus 1.

00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:35.410
That could be minus 1.

00:37:35.410 --> 00:37:40.142
Oh, sorry, 1, 0 gives me 0 and
0 minus 1 on 1 gives me minus 1,

00:37:40.142 --> 00:37:41.350
which is 1 with a minus sign.

00:37:41.350 --> 00:37:43.870
That's a minus sign.

00:37:43.870 --> 00:37:45.620
So this works out like a champ.

00:37:45.620 --> 00:37:47.790
And S squared, meanwhile,
is equal to-- well,

00:37:47.790 --> 00:37:50.810
it's got to give me h
bar squared times 3/4

00:37:50.810 --> 00:37:52.715
for both of these vectors.

00:37:52.715 --> 00:37:54.340
So h bar squared--
and meanwhile, these

00:37:54.340 --> 00:37:58.730
are eigenstates-- h bar squared
times 3/4 times 1, 0, 0, 1.

00:38:04.330 --> 00:38:10.240
So we know one other
fact, which was brought up

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:14.320
just a minute ago, which
was that if we take S plus

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:16.820
and you act on the state
0, 1, what should you get?

00:38:20.510 --> 00:38:23.150
If you raise your 1-- 1, 0.

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:24.000
Great.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:27.609
So we also worked out the
normalization coefficient

00:38:27.609 --> 00:38:28.400
on the problem set.

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:31.860
And that normalization
coefficient turns out to be 1.

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.600
And let's be careful--
we've got an h

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:38.020
bar, for dimensional
analysis reasons.

00:38:38.020 --> 00:38:41.450
So meanwhile, S minus,
similarly, on 0,

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:45.220
1, is equal to 0.

00:38:45.220 --> 00:38:50.305
And S plus on 0, 1,
is equal to-- oh,

00:38:50.305 --> 00:38:51.430
sorry, we already did that.

00:38:51.430 --> 00:38:55.390
We want S minus on 1, 0.

00:38:55.390 --> 00:38:58.660
Let's see-- S minus on--
we want S plus on 1,

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:02.740
0 is equal to-- right, 0.

00:39:02.740 --> 00:39:10.560
And S minus on 1, 0 is
equal to h bar 0, 1.

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:12.640
OK, so putting
all this together,

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:14.960
you can pretty quickly
get that S plus

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:20.870
is equal to-- we
need an h bar and we

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:28.300
need it to raise the lower
one and kill the top state.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:31.520
So on 1, 0, what does S plus do?

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:33.880
That gives us 0 that gives us 0.

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:34.920
Good.

00:39:34.920 --> 00:39:37.409
And on the lowered
state, 0, 1, that

00:39:37.409 --> 00:39:38.950
gives me a 1 up top
and that gives me

00:39:38.950 --> 00:39:40.810
a 0 downstairs, so it
works out like this.

00:39:40.810 --> 00:39:41.650
So we've got h bar.

00:39:41.650 --> 00:39:48.500
Similarly, S minus is equal
to h bar times 0, 0, 1, 0.

00:39:52.610 --> 00:39:55.990
So we've got these
guys-- so much

00:39:55.990 --> 00:40:00.606
from just the definitions
of raising and lowering.

00:40:00.606 --> 00:40:01.980
And by taking
inner products, you

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:05.540
can just derive those
two lines from these.

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:16.140
But notice that Sx is equal
to S plus plus S minus upon 2,

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:23.220
and Sy is equal to S plus
minus S minus upon 2i.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:33.470
So this tells us that Sx is
equal to h bar upon 2 times

00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:36.040
S plus-- we're going to
get a 1 here-- plus S

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:39.930
minus-- we're going to
get a 1 here-- 0, 1, 1, 0.

00:40:39.930 --> 00:40:47.125
And Sy is equal to, again,
upon 2i times h bar, h

00:40:47.125 --> 00:40:52.590
bar upon 2i, times S plus, which
is going to give me 1 and minus

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:55.540
S minus which is going
to give me minus 1, 0, 0.

00:40:55.540 --> 00:41:01.458
But we can pull this i in,
so 1/i is like minus i.

00:41:01.458 --> 00:41:07.160
So minus i times minus
1 is going to give me i

00:41:07.160 --> 00:41:09.580
and minus i times 1
is going to give me i.

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:14.952
So--

00:41:14.952 --> 00:41:16.422
AUDIENCE: Shouldn't
it be minus i?

00:41:16.422 --> 00:41:17.130
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:41:17.130 --> 00:41:18.074
Yeah, did I write i?

00:41:18.074 --> 00:41:19.240
That should've been minus i.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:19.739
Thank you.

00:41:23.390 --> 00:41:27.850
So now we have a nice
representation of these spin

00:41:27.850 --> 00:41:32.380
operations, of the
spin operators.

00:41:32.380 --> 00:41:42.730
And explicitly we have that
Sx is equal to h bar upon 2 0,

00:41:42.730 --> 00:41:50.990
1, 1, 0, Sy is equal to h
bar upon 2 0, minus i, i, 0.

00:41:50.990 --> 00:41:57.090
And Sz is equal to h bar
upon 2 1, 0, 0, minus 1.

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:02.325
So why is Sz the only
one that's diagonal?

00:42:05.970 --> 00:42:07.650
Is it something
special about Sz?

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:15.670
AUDIENCE: I mean, we've chosen
z as the axis along which

00:42:15.670 --> 00:42:17.370
to project S squared.

00:42:17.370 --> 00:42:18.320
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:42:18.320 --> 00:42:19.930
So the thing that's
special about Sz

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:22.130
is that at the very
beginning of this,

00:42:22.130 --> 00:42:25.860
we decided to work in a
basis of eigenstates of Sz,

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:28.220
with definite values of Sz.

00:42:28.220 --> 00:42:31.250
So if they have definite
values, then acting with Sz

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:32.740
is just going to
give you a number.

00:42:32.740 --> 00:42:34.490
That's what it is to
be a diagonal matrix.

00:42:34.490 --> 00:42:38.300
You act on a basis vector,
you just get a number out.

00:42:38.300 --> 00:42:45.300
So we started out by working
in the eigenbasis of Sz.

00:42:45.300 --> 00:42:55.515
And as a consequence, we
find that Sz is diagonal.

00:42:55.515 --> 00:42:57.140
And this is a general
truth that you'll

00:42:57.140 --> 00:43:06.320
discover in matrix
mechanics when

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:08.830
you work in the
eigenbasis of an operator,

00:43:08.830 --> 00:43:11.980
that operator is represented
by a diagonal matrix.

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:14.600
And so we often say, rather
than to work in an eigenbasis,

00:43:14.600 --> 00:43:15.900
we often say, to diagonalize.

00:43:15.900 --> 00:43:17.066
Yeah.

00:43:17.066 --> 00:43:19.360
AUDIENCE: Are the
signs right for Sy?

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:24.206
Because if we had h bar over
2i, and as we initially had a 1

00:43:24.206 --> 00:43:27.045
in the top right and minus
1 in the bottom left,

00:43:27.045 --> 00:43:28.400
shouldn't we just multiply by i?

00:43:28.400 --> 00:43:30.316
PROFESSOR: I'm pretty
sure-- so originally, we

00:43:30.316 --> 00:43:32.369
had a downstairs i, right?

00:43:32.369 --> 00:43:34.160
So let's think about
what this looked like.

00:43:34.160 --> 00:43:36.161
This was 1 and minus 1, right?

00:43:36.161 --> 00:43:36.660
Agreed?

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:38.850
So this is minus 1 over i.

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:39.760
So we pull in the i.

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:43.230
So that we go from minus
1 to minus 1 over i.

00:43:43.230 --> 00:43:46.430
And we go from 1 to 1 over i.

00:43:46.430 --> 00:43:49.280
And I claim that one
over i is minus i.

00:43:49.280 --> 00:43:50.090
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:50.673
PROFESSOR: OK?

00:43:50.673 --> 00:43:52.400
And minus 1 over i is i.

00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:53.003
That cool?

00:43:53.003 --> 00:43:53.830
Good.

00:43:53.830 --> 00:44:00.860
OK, so this is i and minus i.

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:02.380
I always get that
screwy, but it's

00:44:02.380 --> 00:44:04.740
useful to memorize
these matrices.

00:44:04.740 --> 00:44:07.210
You might think it's a little
silly to memorize matrices.

00:44:07.210 --> 00:44:09.630
But these turn out to
be ridiculously useful

00:44:09.630 --> 00:44:10.880
and they come up all the time.

00:44:10.880 --> 00:44:13.140
This is called sigma x.

00:44:13.140 --> 00:44:14.986
This is called sigma y.

00:44:14.986 --> 00:44:16.110
And this is called sigma z.

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:19.820
And different people decide
whether to put the 1/2 in there

00:44:19.820 --> 00:44:22.020
or not, the h bar
does not go in there.

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:24.722
Some people put in the 2, some
people don't put in the 1/2,

00:44:24.722 --> 00:44:25.680
it's a matter of taste.

00:44:25.680 --> 00:44:30.150
Just be careful and be
consistent, as usual.

00:44:30.150 --> 00:44:33.550
And these are called the
Pauli matrices because A,

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:36.822
we really like Pauli and
B, Pauli introduced them.

00:44:36.822 --> 00:44:39.480
Although he didn't actually
introduce them in some sense--

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:41.890
this mathematical
structure was introduced

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:43.380
ages and ages and ages ago.

00:44:43.380 --> 00:44:46.370
But physicists cite
the physicist, not

00:44:46.370 --> 00:44:48.850
the mathematician.

00:44:48.850 --> 00:44:51.310
OK I'm not saying that's good.

00:44:51.310 --> 00:44:53.600
I'm just saying it happens.

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:56.255
So notice a
consequence of these.

00:44:56.255 --> 00:44:58.380
An important consequence
of these-- the whole point

00:44:58.380 --> 00:45:02.700
here was to build a
representation of the spin

00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:03.620
operators.

00:45:03.620 --> 00:45:05.490
Now whatever else the
spin operators do,

00:45:05.490 --> 00:45:07.620
they had better satisfy
that computation relation,

00:45:07.620 --> 00:45:09.180
otherwise they're not
really spin operators.

00:45:09.180 --> 00:45:11.200
That's what we mean by
being spin operators.

00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:12.200
So let's check.

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:17.892
Is it true that Sx commutator
with Sy is equal to i h bar Sz?

00:45:17.892 --> 00:45:19.330
So this is a question mark.

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:23.270
And let's check.

00:45:23.270 --> 00:45:24.660
Let's do the commutator.

00:45:24.660 --> 00:45:27.900
From the Sx, we're going
to get an h bar upon 2.

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:30.530
From the Sy, from each Sy, we're
going to get a factor of h bar

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:33.155
upon 2, so I'll just write that
as h bar upon 2 squared-- times

00:45:33.155 --> 00:45:35.690
the commutator of two
matrices-- 0, 1, 1,

00:45:35.690 --> 00:45:39.730
0 commutator with
0, minus i, i, 0.

00:45:42.250 --> 00:45:45.990
This is equal to h bar
squared upon 4 times--

00:45:45.990 --> 00:45:46.990
let's write this out.

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:50.250
The first term is going to be
this matrix times this matrix.

00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:54.690
That's going to be, again,
a matrix-- 0, 1, 0, 1.

00:45:54.690 --> 00:45:56.030
So that first one is a 1.

00:45:56.030 --> 00:45:59.360
0, 1, minus i-- oh,
sorry, that's an i.

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:01.890
0, 1, that's an i,
that's a minus i.

00:46:01.890 --> 00:46:04.056
So 0, 1, 0, i gives me an i.

00:46:04.056 --> 00:46:06.770
0, 1, minus i, 0 gives me a 0.

00:46:06.770 --> 00:46:09.380
Second row-- 1, 0,
0, i gives me 0.

00:46:09.380 --> 00:46:15.180
And 1, 0, minus i,
0 gives me minus i.

00:46:15.180 --> 00:46:17.790
And then the second term is
the flipped order, right?

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:18.680
The commutator term.

00:46:18.680 --> 00:46:23.680
So we get minus the commutator
term, which is going to be 0,

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:25.180
minus i, 0, 1.

00:46:25.180 --> 00:46:28.500
That gives me minus i.

00:46:28.500 --> 00:46:32.620
0, minus i, 1, 0,
that gives me 0.

00:46:32.620 --> 00:46:36.830
Bottom row-- i, 0, 0, 1-- 0.

00:46:36.830 --> 00:46:39.430
And i, 0, 1, 0 give me i.

00:46:39.430 --> 00:46:41.150
OK, so notice what
we get this is

00:46:41.150 --> 00:46:45.040
equal to h bar squared upon 4.

00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:47.650
And both of those matrices
are the same thing.

00:46:47.650 --> 00:46:52.170
Those matrices are both i, 0,
0, minus i with minus i, 0, 0,

00:46:52.170 --> 00:47:02.190
i, giving us i, 0, 0, minus
i times 2 from the two terms.

00:47:02.190 --> 00:47:04.370
The 2's cancel,
and this gives me

00:47:04.370 --> 00:47:13.600
h bar squared upon 2
times i, 0, 0, minus i.

00:47:13.600 --> 00:47:23.050
But this is also known as--
pulling out an i and an h bar--

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:27.520
times h bar upon 2
1, 0, 0, minus 1.

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:29.610
This is equal to i h bar Sz.

00:47:34.580 --> 00:47:37.710
So these matrices represent
the angular momentum

00:47:37.710 --> 00:47:39.460
commutators quite nicely.

00:47:42.544 --> 00:47:44.460
And in fact, if you
check, all the commutators

00:47:44.460 --> 00:47:47.510
work out beautifully.

00:47:47.510 --> 00:47:50.110
So quickly, just
as a reminder, what

00:47:50.110 --> 00:47:51.690
are the possible
measurable values

00:47:51.690 --> 00:47:54.020
of Sz for the spin 1/2 system?

00:47:56.834 --> 00:47:58.250
What possible
values could you get

00:47:58.250 --> 00:48:03.050
if you measured Sz,
spin in the z direction?

00:48:03.050 --> 00:48:05.720
Yeah, plus or
minus h bar upon 2.

00:48:05.720 --> 00:48:10.050
Now what about the eigenvectors?

00:48:10.050 --> 00:48:11.870
What are they-- of Sz?

00:48:14.492 --> 00:48:16.200
In this notation,
there are these states.

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:17.991
There's one eigenvector,
there's the other.

00:48:17.991 --> 00:48:19.970
But let's ask the same
question about Sx.

00:48:19.970 --> 00:48:22.150
So for Sx, what are the
allowed eigenvalues?

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:27.295
Well, we can answer
this in two ways.

00:48:27.295 --> 00:48:29.420
The first way we can answer
this is by saying look,

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:30.235
there's nothing deep about z.

00:48:30.235 --> 00:48:32.100
It was just the stupid
direction we started with.

00:48:32.100 --> 00:48:34.490
We could have started by working
with the eigenbasis of Sx

00:48:34.490 --> 00:48:36.364
and we would've found
exactly the same story.

00:48:36.364 --> 00:48:38.100
So it must be plus or
minus h bar upon 2.

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:40.230
But the reason you make
that argument is A,

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:42.330
it's slick and B,
it's the only one

00:48:42.330 --> 00:48:45.680
you can make without knowing
something else about how

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:47.330
Sx acts.

00:48:47.330 --> 00:48:48.620
But now we know what Sx is.

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:51.220
Sx is that operator.

00:48:51.220 --> 00:48:54.570
So now we can ask, what are the
eigenvalues of that operator?

00:48:54.570 --> 00:48:58.920
And if you compute the
eigenvalues of that operator,

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:00.700
you find that there
are two eigenvalues

00:49:00.700 --> 00:49:07.970
Sx is equal to h
bar upon 2 and Sx

00:49:07.970 --> 00:49:09.746
is equal to minus h bar upon 2.

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:27.744
And now I can ask, well,
what are the eigenvectors?

00:49:27.744 --> 00:49:29.160
Now, we know what
the eigenvectors

00:49:29.160 --> 00:49:30.534
are because we
can just construct

00:49:30.534 --> 00:49:32.080
the eigenvectors of Sx plus.

00:49:32.080 --> 00:49:36.370
And if you construct the
eigenvectors of Sx plus--

00:49:36.370 --> 00:49:37.560
should I take the time?

00:49:37.560 --> 00:49:40.460
How many people want me to
do the eigenvectors of Sx

00:49:40.460 --> 00:49:41.210
explicitly?

00:49:41.210 --> 00:49:41.880
Yeah, that's kind
of what I figured.

00:49:41.880 --> 00:49:42.560
OK, good.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:45.520
So the eigenvectors of Sx
are, for example, on 1,

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:55.550
1 is equal to-- well, Sx
on 1, 1, the first term,

00:49:55.550 --> 00:49:57.547
that 0, 1, is going
to give me a 1, the 1,

00:49:57.547 --> 00:49:58.630
0 is going to give me a 1.

00:49:58.630 --> 00:50:03.130
So this is h bar upon 2
coefficient of Sx on 1, 1.

00:50:03.130 --> 00:50:08.560
And Sx on 1, minus 1 is going
to give me h bar upon 2 minus 1,

00:50:08.560 --> 00:50:11.380
minus 1, because
all Sx does is swap

00:50:11.380 --> 00:50:14.120
the first and second components.

00:50:14.120 --> 00:50:16.610
So it gives me minus
1, takes it to the top,

00:50:16.610 --> 00:50:18.200
but that's just an
overall minus sign.

00:50:18.200 --> 00:50:20.480
So again, we have the correct
eigenvalues, plus and minus

00:50:20.480 --> 00:50:22.290
h bar upon 2, and now
we know the eigenvector.

00:50:22.290 --> 00:50:23.410
So what does this tell us?

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:26.720
What does it tell us that
up in the x direction

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:32.410
is equal to 1 over root 2 if
I normalize things properly.

00:50:32.410 --> 00:50:35.384
Up in the z direction plus
down in the z direction.

00:50:35.384 --> 00:50:36.675
That's what this is telling me.

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:45.720
This vector is equal to up
in the z direction-- that's

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:48.280
this guy-- plus down
in the z direction.

00:50:51.630 --> 00:50:54.307
But this isn't
properly normalized,

00:50:54.307 --> 00:50:56.515
and properly normalizing it
gives us this expression.

00:51:00.010 --> 00:51:01.514
So what does this tell us?

00:51:01.514 --> 00:51:03.930
This tells us that if we happen
to know that the system is

00:51:03.930 --> 00:51:07.990
in the state with angular
momentum, or spin,

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:11.590
angular momentum in the x
direction being plus 1/2, then

00:51:11.590 --> 00:51:14.640
the probability to measure
up in the z direction

00:51:14.640 --> 00:51:17.210
in a subsequent
measurement is 1/2.

00:51:17.210 --> 00:51:20.610
And the probability to
measure down is 1/2.

00:51:20.610 --> 00:51:22.630
If you know it's up
in the x direction,

00:51:22.630 --> 00:51:26.190
the probability of measuring
up in the z or down in the z

00:51:26.190 --> 00:51:26.822
are equal.

00:51:26.822 --> 00:51:27.530
You're at chance.

00:51:27.530 --> 00:51:29.299
You're at even odds.

00:51:29.299 --> 00:51:30.340
Everyone agree with that?

00:51:30.340 --> 00:51:33.530
That's the meaning
of this expression.

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:36.580
And similarly, down in the
x direction is equal to 1

00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:39.820
over root 2, up
in the z direction

00:51:39.820 --> 00:51:42.130
minus down in the z direction.

00:51:42.130 --> 00:51:44.730
And we get that from here.

00:51:44.730 --> 00:51:48.810
This state is explicitly, by
construction, the eigenstate

00:51:48.810 --> 00:51:51.200
of Sx as we've constructed Sx.

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:52.940
And we have a natural
expression in terms

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:55.602
of the z eigenvectors
up and down.

00:51:55.602 --> 00:51:57.310
That's what this
expression is giving us.

00:51:57.310 --> 00:52:00.910
It gives us an expression
of the Sx eigenvector

00:52:00.910 --> 00:52:02.400
in the basis of Sz eigenvectors.

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:08.590
So for example, this tells
you that the probability

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:12.940
to measure up in the
z direction, given

00:52:12.940 --> 00:52:15.272
that we measured down
in the x direction

00:52:15.272 --> 00:52:17.230
first-- so this is the
conditional probability.

00:52:17.230 --> 00:52:19.470
Suppose I first measured
down in the x direction,

00:52:19.470 --> 00:52:21.219
what's the probability
that I subsequently

00:52:21.219 --> 00:52:22.580
measure up in the z direction?

00:52:22.580 --> 00:52:25.450
This is equal to--
well, it's the norm

00:52:25.450 --> 00:52:27.640
squared of the
expansion coefficient.

00:52:27.640 --> 00:52:31.910
So first down in the x
direction and the probability

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:37.424
that we're up in the z direction
is 1 upon root 2 squared.

00:52:37.424 --> 00:52:38.840
Usual rules of
quantum mechanics--

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:41.090
take the expansion coefficient,
take its norm squared,

00:52:41.090 --> 00:52:42.470
that's the probability-- 1/2.

00:52:48.875 --> 00:52:54.090
And we can do exactly
the same thing for Sy.

00:52:57.190 --> 00:53:01.196
So let's do the
same thing for Sy

00:53:01.196 --> 00:53:03.070
without actually working
out all the details.

00:53:11.060 --> 00:53:17.920
So doing the same thing for
Sy, up in the y direction

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:24.070
is equal to 1 upon root 2 times
up in the z direction plus i

00:53:24.070 --> 00:53:27.460
down in the z direction.

00:53:27.460 --> 00:53:32.642
And down in the y direction
is equal to 1 upon root 2

00:53:32.642 --> 00:53:38.400
up in the z direction minus
i down in the z direction.

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:40.790
And I encourage you to
check your knowledge

00:53:40.790 --> 00:53:43.339
by deriving these
eigenvectors, which

00:53:43.339 --> 00:53:45.130
you can do given our
representations of Sy.

00:53:47.770 --> 00:53:51.020
Now here's a nice thing that
we're going to use later.

00:53:51.020 --> 00:53:52.160
Consider the following.

00:53:52.160 --> 00:53:56.470
Consider the operator
S theta, which

00:53:56.470 --> 00:54:02.984
I'm going to define as cosine
theta Sz plus-- oh, sorry.

00:54:02.984 --> 00:54:04.650
I'm not even going
to write it that way.

00:54:04.650 --> 00:54:09.800
So what I mean by S
theta is equal to-- take

00:54:09.800 --> 00:54:15.380
our spherical directions and
consider an angle in the-- this

00:54:15.380 --> 00:54:22.910
is x, let's say, y, x, z--
consider an angle theta down

00:54:22.910 --> 00:54:31.700
in the zx plane, and we
can ask, what is the spin

00:54:31.700 --> 00:54:34.330
operator along the
direction theta?

00:54:34.330 --> 00:54:37.170
What's the angular momentum
in the direction theta?

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:41.469
If theta, for example, is
equal to pi/2, this is Sx.

00:54:41.469 --> 00:54:43.010
So I'm just defining
a spin operator,

00:54:43.010 --> 00:54:45.426
which is the angular momentum
along a particular direction

00:54:45.426 --> 00:54:47.610
theta in the xz plane.

00:54:47.610 --> 00:54:49.025
Everyone cool with that?

00:54:49.025 --> 00:54:51.150
This is going to turn out
to be very useful for us,

00:54:51.150 --> 00:54:53.389
and I encourage you to
derive the following.

00:54:53.389 --> 00:54:55.180
And if you don't derive
the following, then

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:57.760
hopefully it will be
done in your recitations.

00:54:57.760 --> 00:55:00.910
Well, I will chat with your
recitation instructors.

00:55:00.910 --> 00:55:02.970
And if you do
this, then what are

00:55:02.970 --> 00:55:05.050
we going to get for the
eigenvalues of S theta?

00:55:08.530 --> 00:55:10.510
What possible eigenvalues
could S theta have?

00:55:17.915 --> 00:55:18.790
[? AUDIENCE: None. ?]

00:55:18.790 --> 00:55:19.022
PROFESSOR: Good.

00:55:19.022 --> 00:55:19.610
Why?

00:55:19.610 --> 00:55:21.960
AUDIENCE: Because it can't
have any other redirection

00:55:21.960 --> 00:55:24.387
[INAUDIBLE] no matter
where you start.

00:55:24.387 --> 00:55:25.220
PROFESSOR: Fabulous.

00:55:25.220 --> 00:55:25.720
OK.

00:55:25.720 --> 00:55:28.280
So the answer that
was given is that it's

00:55:28.280 --> 00:55:30.690
the same, plus or
minus h bar upon 2

00:55:30.690 --> 00:55:33.719
as Sz, or indeed as Sx or
Sy, because it can't possibly

00:55:33.719 --> 00:55:35.760
matter what direction you
chose at the beginning.

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:37.950
I could have called
this direction theta z.

00:55:37.950 --> 00:55:39.300
How do you stop me?

00:55:39.300 --> 00:55:41.080
We could have done that.

00:55:41.080 --> 00:55:42.184
We didn't.

00:55:42.184 --> 00:55:43.600
That was our first
wave answering.

00:55:43.600 --> 00:55:45.260
Second wave answering is what?

00:55:45.260 --> 00:55:48.230
Well, construct the
operator S theta

00:55:48.230 --> 00:55:52.115
and find its eigenvectors
and eigenvalues.

00:55:52.115 --> 00:55:53.365
So I encourage you to do that.

00:55:53.365 --> 00:55:58.290
And what you find
is that, of course,

00:55:58.290 --> 00:56:01.110
the eigenvalues are plus
or minus h bar upon 2

00:56:01.110 --> 00:56:09.140
and up at the angle theta is
equal to cosine of theta upon 2

00:56:09.140 --> 00:56:13.020
up in the z direction
plus sine of theta

00:56:13.020 --> 00:56:17.310
upon 2 down in the z direction.

00:56:17.310 --> 00:56:21.540
And down theta is
equal to cosine theta

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:27.930
upon 2 up in the z direction
minus sine of theta

00:56:27.930 --> 00:56:35.050
over 2 down in the z direction.

00:56:35.050 --> 00:56:35.872
Oops, no.

00:56:35.872 --> 00:56:36.580
I got that wrong.

00:56:36.580 --> 00:56:39.530
This is sine, and
this is minus cosine.

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:40.624
Good.

00:56:40.624 --> 00:56:41.540
That makes more sense.

00:56:45.020 --> 00:56:45.520
OK.

00:56:45.520 --> 00:56:46.822
So let's just sanity check.

00:56:46.822 --> 00:56:48.530
These guys should be
properly normalized.

00:56:48.530 --> 00:56:51.190
So if we take the norm
squared of this guy,

00:56:51.190 --> 00:56:53.175
the cross terms vanish
because up z and down z

00:56:53.175 --> 00:56:54.366
are orthogonal states.

00:56:54.366 --> 00:56:56.740
So we're going to get a co
squared plus the sine squared.

00:56:56.740 --> 00:56:57.240
That's 1.

00:56:57.240 --> 00:56:58.551
So that's properly normalized.

00:56:58.551 --> 00:56:59.550
Same thing for this guy.

00:56:59.550 --> 00:57:00.570
The minus doesn't
change anything

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:01.569
because we norm squared.

00:57:01.569 --> 00:57:03.271
Now, I'll check that
they're orthogonal.

00:57:03.271 --> 00:57:05.770
If we take this guy dotted into
this guy, everything's real.

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:09.700
So we get a cosine
from up up, we're

00:57:09.700 --> 00:57:11.022
going to get a cosine sine.

00:57:11.022 --> 00:57:13.480
And from down down, we're going
to get a minus cosine sine.

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:14.287
So that gives us 0.

00:57:14.287 --> 00:57:15.870
So these guys are
orthogonal, and they

00:57:15.870 --> 00:57:18.630
satisfy all the nice
properties we want.

00:57:18.630 --> 00:57:25.245
So this is a good check--
do this-- of your knowledge.

00:57:25.245 --> 00:57:27.120
And if we had problem
sets allowed this week,

00:57:27.120 --> 00:57:30.080
I would give you this in your
problem set, but we don't.

00:57:35.879 --> 00:57:36.830
Yeah, OK.

00:57:44.737 --> 00:57:45.695
Suppose that I measure.

00:57:45.695 --> 00:57:47.880
So I want to use these
states for something.

00:57:47.880 --> 00:57:58.330
Suppose that I
measure Sz and find

00:57:58.330 --> 00:58:02.690
Sz is equal to 1/2 h
bar plus h bar upon 2,

00:58:02.690 --> 00:58:06.010
OK, at some moment in time.

00:58:10.232 --> 00:58:11.190
First question is easy.

00:58:11.190 --> 00:58:14.190
What's the state of the system
subsequent to that measurement?

00:58:17.004 --> 00:58:19.350
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:19.350 --> 00:58:21.777
PROFESSOR: Man, you
all are so quiet today.

00:58:21.777 --> 00:58:24.110
What's the state of the system
subsequent to measurement

00:58:24.110 --> 00:58:26.695
that Sz is plus h bar upon 2?

00:58:26.695 --> 00:58:28.406
AUDIENCE: Up z.

00:58:28.406 --> 00:58:29.080
PROFESSOR: Up z.

00:58:29.080 --> 00:58:29.580
Good.

00:58:29.580 --> 00:58:36.700
So our state psi is
up z upon measurement,

00:58:36.700 --> 00:58:38.915
OK, after measurement.

00:58:48.540 --> 00:58:50.805
And I need new chalk.

00:58:50.805 --> 00:58:51.305
OK.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:59:04.316
Now, if I measure Sx, so 1, 2,
measure Sx, what will I get?

00:59:04.316 --> 00:59:07.250
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:07.250 --> 00:59:08.300
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:59:08.300 --> 00:59:11.726
What values will I observe
with what probabilities?

00:59:11.726 --> 00:59:13.600
Well, first off, what
are the possible values

00:59:13.600 --> 00:59:14.607
that you can measure?

00:59:14.607 --> 00:59:16.010
AUDIENCE: Plus or
minus h bar over 2.

00:59:16.010 --> 00:59:17.801
PROFESSOR: Right, the
possible eigenvalues,

00:59:17.801 --> 00:59:20.760
so which is plus or minus
h bar upon 2, but with what

00:59:20.760 --> 00:59:21.720
probability?

00:59:21.720 --> 00:59:22.595
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:22.595 --> 00:59:23.386
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:59:23.386 --> 00:59:25.200
So we know this from
the eigenstate of Sx.

00:59:25.200 --> 00:59:28.040
If we know that we're
in the state up z,

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:30.400
we can take linear
combinations of this guy

00:59:30.400 --> 00:59:35.810
to show that up z is
equal to 1 over root 2.

00:59:35.810 --> 00:59:37.090
So let's just check.

00:59:37.090 --> 00:59:40.460
If we add these two
together, up x and down x,

00:59:40.460 --> 00:59:43.240
if we add them
together, we'll get 1/2,

00:59:43.240 --> 00:59:50.810
1/2, 2/2, a root 2 times up
z, is up x plus down x, up x

00:59:50.810 --> 00:59:56.060
plus down x, dividing
through by the 1/2.

00:59:56.060 --> 00:59:58.290
So here we've expressed
up in the z direction

00:59:58.290 --> 01:00:01.810
in a basis of x and y, which
is what we're supposed to do.

01:00:01.810 --> 01:00:04.920
So the probability that
I measure a plus 1/2

01:00:04.920 --> 01:00:11.016
as x is equal to
plus 1/2 h bar upon 2

01:00:11.016 --> 01:00:14.290
is equal to 1 over
root 2 squared, so 1/2.

01:00:14.290 --> 01:00:19.780
And ditto, Sx is equal
to minus h bar upon 2.

01:00:19.780 --> 01:00:21.271
Same probability.

01:00:21.271 --> 01:00:21.770
OK?

01:00:21.770 --> 01:00:22.740
What about Sy?

01:00:28.680 --> 01:00:30.310
Again, we get one of two values.

01:00:30.310 --> 01:00:33.770
Oops, plus or
minus h bar upon 2.

01:00:33.770 --> 01:00:38.070
But the probability of
measuring plus is equal to 1/2,

01:00:38.070 --> 01:00:47.050
and the probability that we
measure minus 1/2 is 1/2.

01:00:47.050 --> 01:00:49.310
That's h bar upon 2.

01:00:49.310 --> 01:00:49.810
OK?

01:00:49.810 --> 01:00:51.018
So this should look familiar.

01:00:54.920 --> 01:00:57.040
Going back to the
very first lecture,

01:00:57.040 --> 01:01:00.260
hardness was spin
in the z direction,

01:01:00.260 --> 01:01:05.624
and color was spin in
the x direction, I guess.

01:01:05.624 --> 01:01:07.290
And we added, at one
point, a third one,

01:01:07.290 --> 01:01:09.230
which I think I
called whimsy, which

01:01:09.230 --> 01:01:12.740
is equal to spin
in the y direction.

01:01:12.740 --> 01:01:13.240
OK?

01:01:13.240 --> 01:01:15.085
And now all of the
box operation that we

01:01:15.085 --> 01:01:17.210
used in that very first
lecture, you can understand

01:01:17.210 --> 01:01:19.140
is nothing other than
stringing together

01:01:19.140 --> 01:01:22.100
chains of Stern-Gerlach
experiments

01:01:22.100 --> 01:01:24.630
doing Sx, Sy, and Sz.

01:01:24.630 --> 01:01:27.182
So let's be explicit about that.

01:01:27.182 --> 01:01:29.510
Let's make that concrete.

01:01:29.510 --> 01:01:32.760
Actually, let's do that here.

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:38.900
So for example, suppose
we put a random electron

01:01:38.900 --> 01:01:43.691
into an Sz color box.

01:01:43.691 --> 01:01:44.190
OK.

01:01:44.190 --> 01:01:46.620
Some are going to
come out up, and some

01:01:46.620 --> 01:01:51.520
are going to come out
down in the z direction.

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:57.210
And if we send this into
now an Sx color box,

01:01:57.210 --> 01:01:59.610
this is going to give us
either up in the x direction

01:01:59.610 --> 01:02:02.070
or down in the x direction.

01:02:02.070 --> 01:02:06.200
And what we'll get
out is 50-50, right?

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:06.700
OK.

01:02:06.700 --> 01:02:10.040
So let's take the ones
that came out down.

01:02:10.040 --> 01:02:15.450
And if we send those back
into an Sz, what do we get?

01:02:15.450 --> 01:02:16.770
AUDIENCE: 50-50.

01:02:16.770 --> 01:02:21.450
PROFESSOR: Yeah, 50-50,
because down x is 1 over 2 up z

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:23.091
plus 1 over 2 down z.

01:02:23.091 --> 01:02:25.340
What was going on in that
very first experiment, where

01:02:25.340 --> 01:02:28.200
we did hardness,
color, hardness?

01:02:28.200 --> 01:02:29.650
Superposition.

01:02:29.650 --> 01:02:33.680
And what superposition
was a hard electron?

01:02:33.680 --> 01:02:37.320
It was 1 over a 2,
white plus black.

01:02:37.320 --> 01:02:40.130
We know precisely which
superposition, and here it is.

01:02:40.130 --> 01:02:40.890
OK?

01:02:40.890 --> 01:02:42.990
And now, let's do that
last experiment, where

01:02:42.990 --> 01:02:51.510
we take these guys, Sx down, and
I'm turning this upside down,

01:02:51.510 --> 01:02:52.140
beam joiners.

01:02:52.140 --> 01:02:56.059
We take the up in the x
direction and the down

01:02:56.059 --> 01:02:58.100
in the x direction, and
we combine them together,

01:02:58.100 --> 01:03:02.772
and we put them back
into Sz, what do we get?

01:03:02.772 --> 01:03:03.730
Well, what's the state?

01:03:03.730 --> 01:03:09.600
1 over root 2 down x
plus 1 over root 2 up x?

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:12.030
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:12.030 --> 01:03:14.580
PROFESSOR: It's up z.

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:18.640
Up z into an Sz
box, what do we get?

01:03:18.640 --> 01:03:19.285
Up z with 100%.

01:03:22.220 --> 01:03:25.660
That's white with 100%, or
I'm sorry, hard with 100%.

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:27.942
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
down z with a down z.

01:03:27.942 --> 01:03:28.650
PROFESSOR: Sorry.

01:03:28.650 --> 01:03:29.462
AUDIENCE: You put in down.

01:03:29.462 --> 01:03:30.420
PROFESSOR: Oh, I put in down.

01:03:30.420 --> 01:03:31.128
Shoot, I'm sorry.

01:03:31.128 --> 01:03:32.910
Well, yeah, indeed,
I meant to put in up.

01:03:32.910 --> 01:03:35.510
Yes, down z with
100% confidence.

01:03:35.510 --> 01:03:37.230
If we remove the mirror, 50-50.

01:03:37.230 --> 01:03:38.932
If we add in the mirror, 100%.

01:03:38.932 --> 01:03:40.390
And the difference
is whether we're

01:03:40.390 --> 01:03:42.740
taking one component
of the wave function,

01:03:42.740 --> 01:03:46.054
or whether we're superposing
them back together.

01:03:46.054 --> 01:03:47.010
All right?

01:03:47.010 --> 01:03:48.970
Imagine we know we have
a system in this state,

01:03:48.970 --> 01:03:52.590
and I say, look, this component
is also coincidentally very far

01:03:52.590 --> 01:03:55.190
away, and I'm going
to not look at them.

01:03:55.190 --> 01:03:58.656
So of the ones that I look
at, I have 1 over root 2 up x.

01:03:58.656 --> 01:04:00.030
But if I look at
the full system,

01:04:00.030 --> 01:04:03.370
the superimposed system,
that adds together

01:04:03.370 --> 01:04:05.890
to be an eigenstate of Sz.

01:04:05.890 --> 01:04:08.498
These are our color boxes.

01:04:08.498 --> 01:04:08.998
Yeah?

01:04:08.998 --> 01:04:09.736
AUDIENCE: But how
do you know, when

01:04:09.736 --> 01:04:11.458
you put the two beams
to the beam joiner,

01:04:11.458 --> 01:04:13.545
it serves to add their
two states together?

01:04:13.545 --> 01:04:14.670
PROFESSOR: Yeah, excellent.

01:04:14.670 --> 01:04:15.870
This is a very subtle point.

01:04:15.870 --> 01:04:18.420
So here we have to decide what
we mean by the beam splitter.

01:04:18.420 --> 01:04:20.420
And what I'm going to
mean by the beam splitter,

01:04:20.420 --> 01:04:21.510
by the mirrors
and beam joiners--

01:04:21.510 --> 01:04:23.150
so the question is, how do
we know that it does this

01:04:23.150 --> 01:04:24.860
without changing
the superposition?

01:04:24.860 --> 01:04:27.600
And what I want to do
is define this thing

01:04:27.600 --> 01:04:30.410
as the object that takes the
two incident wave functions,

01:04:30.410 --> 01:04:31.780
and it just adds them together.

01:04:31.780 --> 01:04:33.530
It should give me the
direct superposition

01:04:33.530 --> 01:04:35.570
with the appropriate
phases and coefficients.

01:04:35.570 --> 01:04:39.870
So if this was plus up x,
then it stays plus up x.

01:04:39.870 --> 01:04:43.470
If it's minus up x, it's
going to be minus up x.

01:04:43.470 --> 01:04:46.700
Whatever the phase is of
this state, when it gets here

01:04:46.700 --> 01:04:48.780
it just adds together
the two components.

01:04:48.780 --> 01:04:50.570
That's my definition
of that adding box.

01:04:50.570 --> 01:04:54.687
AUDIENCE: So realistically,
what does that look like?

01:04:54.687 --> 01:04:55.520
PROFESSOR: Oh, what?

01:04:55.520 --> 01:04:56.895
You think I'm an
experimentalist?

01:04:56.895 --> 01:04:57.630
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:57.630 --> 01:04:59.600
Look, every time I
try an experiment,

01:04:59.600 --> 01:05:00.910
I get hit by a shark.

01:05:00.910 --> 01:05:01.410
OK?

01:05:01.410 --> 01:05:04.320
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:04.320 --> 01:05:05.500
Yeah, no.

01:05:05.500 --> 01:05:07.480
How you actually implement
that in real systems

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:08.890
is a more complicated story.

01:05:08.890 --> 01:05:11.330
So you should
direct that question

01:05:11.330 --> 01:05:14.720
to Matt, who's a very
good experimentalist.

01:05:14.720 --> 01:05:16.350
OK.

01:05:16.350 --> 01:05:19.570
So finally, let's go back to
the Stern-Gerlach experiment,

01:05:19.570 --> 01:05:22.080
and let's actually run the
Stern-Gerlach experiment.

01:05:22.080 --> 01:05:24.241
I guess I'll do that here.

01:05:24.241 --> 01:05:26.740
So let's think about what the
Stern-Gerlach experiment looks

01:05:26.740 --> 01:05:29.010
like in this notation, and
not just in this notation,

01:05:29.010 --> 01:05:32.590
in the honest language of spin.

01:05:32.590 --> 01:05:35.934
And I'm going to do a slightly
abbreviated version of this

01:05:35.934 --> 01:05:37.600
because you guys can
fill in the details

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:40.981
with your knowledge
of 802 and 803.

01:05:40.981 --> 01:05:41.480
OK.

01:05:41.480 --> 01:05:43.104
So here's the
Stern-Gerlach experiment.

01:05:43.104 --> 01:05:46.635
We have a gradient in
the magnetic field.

01:05:46.635 --> 01:05:47.635
This is the z direction.

01:05:47.635 --> 01:05:52.516
And we have a gradient
where B in the z direction

01:05:52.516 --> 01:06:01.492
has some B0, a
constant plus beta z.

01:06:01.492 --> 01:06:02.300
OK?

01:06:02.300 --> 01:06:06.601
So it's got a constant
piece and a small gradient.

01:06:06.601 --> 01:06:07.600
Everyone cool with that?

01:06:07.600 --> 01:06:09.495
It's just the magnetic field
gets stronger and stronger

