01:19:13.980 --> 01:19:14.946
AUDIENCE: Plus.

01:19:14.946 --> 01:19:16.070
PROFESSOR: Always plus 1/2.

01:19:16.070 --> 01:19:17.600
Did I have to do the
measurement to determine

01:19:17.600 --> 01:19:18.391
that it's plus 1/2.

01:19:21.200 --> 01:19:22.760
No, because I already
know the state,

01:19:22.760 --> 01:19:24.920
so I know exactly what I will
get if I do the experiment.

01:19:24.920 --> 01:19:26.940
I measure up here, and
then the wave function

01:19:26.940 --> 01:19:29.290
is this without the 1 over
root 2, upon measurement.

01:19:29.290 --> 01:19:31.498
But as a consequence, if I
subsequently measure up z,

01:19:31.498 --> 01:19:34.820
the only possible value
is up in the z direction.

01:19:34.820 --> 01:19:36.346
Yeah?

01:19:36.346 --> 01:19:38.660
And this is called entanglement.

01:19:38.660 --> 01:19:46.809
And here it's entanglement of
the position with the spin.

01:19:46.809 --> 01:19:48.350
And next time, what
we'll do is we'll

01:19:48.350 --> 01:19:51.710
study the EPR experiment,
which says the following thing.

01:19:51.710 --> 01:19:54.220
Suppose I take two electrons,
OK, take two electrons,

01:19:54.220 --> 01:19:56.720
and I put them in the state one
is up and the other is down,

01:19:56.720 --> 01:19:59.840
or the first is up and
the second is down.

01:19:59.840 --> 01:20:00.530
All right?

01:20:00.530 --> 01:20:03.610
So up, down plus down, up.

01:20:03.610 --> 01:20:04.120
OK?

01:20:04.120 --> 01:20:07.890
I now take my two electrons, and
I send them to distant places.

01:20:07.890 --> 01:20:12.150
Suppose I measure one of them
to be up in the x direction.

01:20:12.150 --> 01:20:13.570
Yeah?

01:20:13.570 --> 01:20:16.451
Then I know that the other
one is down in that direction.

01:20:16.451 --> 01:20:16.950
Sorry.

01:20:16.950 --> 01:20:18.010
If I measure up in
the z direction,

01:20:18.010 --> 01:20:19.590
I determine the other one
is down in the z direction.

01:20:19.590 --> 01:20:22.449
But suppose someone over here
who's causally disconnected

01:20:22.449 --> 01:20:23.990
measures not spin
in the z direction,

01:20:23.990 --> 01:20:25.940
but spin in the x direction.

01:20:25.940 --> 01:20:28.890
They'll measure one of two
things, either plus or minus.

01:20:28.890 --> 01:20:31.670
Now, knowing what we know,
that it's in the z eigenstate,

01:20:31.670 --> 01:20:36.690
it will be either plus 1/2 in
the x direction or minus 1/2

01:20:36.690 --> 01:20:38.210
in the x direction.

01:20:38.210 --> 01:20:40.270
Suppose I get both measurements.

01:20:40.270 --> 01:20:42.630
The distant person over here
does the measurement of z

01:20:42.630 --> 01:20:46.180
and says, aha, mine is up, so
the other one must be down.

01:20:46.180 --> 01:20:49.830
But the person over here doesn't
measure Sz, they measure Sx,

01:20:49.830 --> 01:20:51.254
and they get that it's plus Sx.

01:20:51.254 --> 01:20:53.170
And what they've done
as a result of these two

01:20:53.170 --> 01:20:55.340
experiments, Einstein,
Podolsky, and Rosen say,

01:20:55.340 --> 01:20:58.460
is this electron has been
measured by the distant guy

01:20:58.460 --> 01:21:05.500
to be spin z down, but by this
guy to be measured spin x up.

01:21:05.500 --> 01:21:10.139
So I know Sx and Sz definitely.

01:21:10.139 --> 01:21:12.680
But that flies in the face of
the uncertainty relation, which

01:21:12.680 --> 01:21:16.250
tells us we can't have spin
z and spin x definitely.

01:21:16.250 --> 01:21:18.122
Einstein and Podolsky
and Rosen say

01:21:18.122 --> 01:21:20.080
there's something missing
in quantum mechanics,

01:21:20.080 --> 01:21:21.496
because I can do
these experiments

01:21:21.496 --> 01:21:26.440
and determine that this
particle is Sz down and Sx up.

01:21:26.440 --> 01:21:32.840
But what quantum
mechanics says is

01:21:32.840 --> 01:21:35.202
that I may have done
the measurement of Sz,

01:21:35.202 --> 01:21:36.660
but that hasn't
determined anything

01:21:36.660 --> 01:21:37.850
about the state over here.

01:21:37.850 --> 01:21:39.600
There is no predetermined value.

01:21:39.600 --> 01:21:41.620
What we need to do is
we need to tease out,

01:21:41.620 --> 01:21:45.130
we need an experimental
version of this tension.

01:21:45.130 --> 01:21:47.444
The experimental
version of this tension,

01:21:47.444 --> 01:21:48.860
fleshed out in the
EPR experiment,

01:21:48.860 --> 01:21:50.010
is called Bell's inequality.

01:21:50.010 --> 01:21:51.670
We studied it in the
very first lecture,

01:21:51.670 --> 01:21:54.211
and we're going to show it's a
violation in the next lecture.

01:21:54.211 --> 01:21:55.470
See you guys next time.

